{{about||the band|Brand New (band)|other uses|Brand New (disambiguation)}} In [[marketing]], '''brand-new''' [[Product (business)|product]]s or [[Service (economics)|service]]s are created and promoted under a new [[brand]]. This is a [[brand strategy]] alongside the [[brand stretching]], [[line extension]] and [[multi-brand]]s strategies.<ref>{{cite book | title=International Marketing, 1E | publisher=Vikas Publishing House Pvt Ltd | author=Rajagopal | year=2009 | pages=239 | isbn=8125918566}}</ref> The brand-new strategy is focused on creating and introducing new products effectively. It involves researching a [[market (economics)|market]] to discover consumer needs that provide a [[market opportunity]], generating ideas on how to approach that opportunity, and [[commercialization|commercializing]] a product by communicating how the product covers the needs.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ufG9A7nMlDsC&lpg=PP1&dq=%22brand%20new%22&hl=en&pg=PA12#v=onepage&q=%22brand%20new%22&f=false | title=Brand New: Solving the Innovation Paradox -- How Great Brands Invent and Launch New Products, Services, and Business Models | publisher=John Wiley & Sons, 2011 |author1=G. Michael Maddock |author2=Luisa C. Uriarte |author3=Paul B. Brown | isbn=1118061454}}</ref>
Companies may introduce brand-new products that replace previous products as a leading function for marketing, instead of making small incremental improvements on existing products.<ref>{{cite book | url=https://books.google.es/books?id=VurHZn3_8IcC&lpg=PA131&dq=%22brand+new%22+marketing+strategy&hl=en&pg=PA131&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q&f=false | title=The Theory of Innovation: Entrepreneurs, Technology and Strategy | publisher=Edward Elgar Publishing | date=1998 | author=Jon Sundbo | pages=131 | isbn=1781008892}}</ref>
