{{for|the South Carolina politician|Irene Krugman Rudnick}}
{{Infobox artist | name = Irene Krugman | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = 1925 | birth_place = [[New York City]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1982|04|15|1925|12|mf=y}} | death_place = [[Morristown, New Jersey]] | nationality = American | education = [[Kansas City Art Institute]], [[New York University]], [[The New School for Social Research]] | field = [[Installation art]] | movement = | works = | awards = | spouse = }}
'''Irene Krugman''' (1925–15 April 1982)<ref name=NYTObit>{{cite newspaper|title=Irene Krugman Dead; Environmental Artist|newspaper=The New York Times|date=17 April 1982|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1982/04/17/obituaries/irene-krugman-dead-environmental-artist.html|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> was an [[United States|American]] artist, known for creating [[installation art|installations]], using a limited number of simplified forms that are repeated on different scales.<ref name=Alloway>{{cite journal|last=Alloway|first=Lawrence|title=Art|journal=The Nation|date=22 April 1978|pages=485–486}}</ref>
Krugman was born in [[New York City]].<ref name=HellerHeller>{{cite book|editor1-last=Heller|editor1-first=Jules|editor2-last=Heller|editor2-first=Nancy G.|title=North American Women Artists of the Twentieth Century: A Biographical Dictionary|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AYxmAgAAQBAJ&pg=PR11|publisher=Routledge|date=1995|page=327}}</ref> She studied at the [[Kansas City Art Institute]], [[New York University]], and the [[New School for Social Research]] with [[Yasuo Kuniyoshi]].<ref name=HellerHeller/> She exhibited widely, in group and solo shows, and her work is owned by the [[Newark Museum]], the [[New Jersey State Museum]], [[Michigan State University]], [[University of Notre Dame]], and [[Rowan University|Rowan University Art Gallery]], among others.<ref name=NYTObit/><ref name=HellerHeller/><ref>{{cite book|url=https://sites.rowan.edu/artgallery/_docs/groundbreaking_catalog.pdf|title=Groundbreaking: The Women of the Sylvia Sleigh Collection|location=Glassboro, NJ|publisher=Rowan University Art Gallery|date=2011|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref>
Her work was praised in ''[[The New York Times]]'' by [[Grace Glueck]], who noted that Krugman's installation at the [[City University of New York]] in 1977 consisted of a "[[mastaba]]-shape" and "mirror-lined boxes of unfinished wood that carry within themselves identical smaller structures reflected by the mirrors," which she called "an imaginative idea, imaginatively executed."<ref name=Glueck>{{cite newspaper|last=Glueck|first=Grace|title=Irene Krugman|newspaper=The New York Times|date=4 February 1977}}</ref> In response to her solo exhibition at [[OK Harris Gallery]] in 1978, a reviewer in ''[[Arts Magazine]]'' characterized Krugman's work as "a model for our perception of the larger world which is also self-reflexive, limited, in other words, by our capacity to measure and know it."<ref name=Malen>{{cite journal|last=Malen|first=Lenore|title=Irene Krugman|journal=Arts Magazine|date=April 1978|page=24}}</ref>
Krugman and her husband, Leonard (1919-1989), lived in [[Morristown, New Jersey]].<ref name=NYTObit/> Their son, Michael Krugman (1951–2016), was a practitioner of [[self-healing]] and developed the Sounder Sleep System, a treatment for people suffering from [[insomnia]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Michael Krugman (1951-2016)|url=https://www.feldenkrais-institute.com/team/michael-krugman|website=Instituto Feldenkrais|accessdate=4 June 2018}}</ref> Irene Krugman died of [[cancer]], aged 56.<ref name=NYTObit/>
